1. Command to check existing downloaded images through crictl
To see every container image currently cached on your node (like the Nginx image that saved you), run:

sudo crictl --image-endpoint unix:///run/containerd/containerd.sock images

2. Commands to ensure Alpine, BusyBox, and HTTP-Echo are always available
To make sure you never get stuck by an internet outage again, you can pre-download these 
common testing images directly into your container runtime cache using these commands:

# Pull Alpine Linux
sudo crictl --image-endpoint unix:///run/containerd/containerd.sock pull alpine:latest

# Pull BusyBox
sudo crictl --image-endpoint unix:///run/containerd/containerd.sock pull busybox:latest

# Pull HashiCorp HTTP Echo (commonly used for routing tests)
sudo crictl --image-endpoint unix:///run/containerd/containerd.sock pull hashicorp/http-echo:latest

If your /etc/crictl.yaml file is missing or empty (which is why crictl gave you that warning earlier), 
you can fix it permanently by running this single command:


sudo crictl config --set runtime-endpoint=unix:///run/containerd/containerd.sock --set image-endpoint=unix:///run/containerd/containerd.sock
Once you run that, you can just type sudo crictl images or sudo crictl pull nginx without ever having to specify the socket path again!


Since you confirmed the socket is /var/run/containerd/containerd.sock, tell crictl to save it. This stops the annoying deprecated endpoint warnings and lets you drop the long --image-endpoint flags.

Run this command:
sudo crictl config --set runtime-endpoint=unix:///var/run/containerd/containerd.sock --set image-endpoint=unix:///var/run/containerd/containerd.sock
